article.description:
Ron Artest scored 19 of his
season-high 30 points in the fourth quarter performance as the Kings beat the Grizzlies 105-93 to climb above .500 for the first time since November.
article.headline: Artest scores 30 as Kings beat Grizz, reach .500
article.linkText: Artest scores 30 as Kings beat Grizz
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Stingy defense. Long streaks of home victories. A playoff berth. Ron Artest made some nutty predictions about the Sacramento Kings when he joined their struggling, jumbled roster six weeks ago. Artest doesn't seem so crazy now to Sacramento's fans. Thanks to the calming influence and gritty play of the NBA's most notorious star, the Kings are starting to look like the team he imagined. Artest scored 19 of his season-high 30 points in the fourth quarter, and Sacramento got back to .500 for the first time since late November with a 105-93 victory over the Memphis Grizzlies on Friday night. Mike Bibby had 19 points and six assists for the Kings in their 11th consecutive home victory. Kenny Thomas had 14 points and 10 rebounds, but Artest carried the revitalized Kings down the stretch of their 16th straight home victory over Memphis. With his 2-year-old daughter in tow after the game, Artest was serene and modest about his gutsy play, which included 10 points in a key 3½-minute stretch of the fourth. He still hasn't lost at home since joining the Kings -- and he claims to see no reason it should ever happen. "When I got here, this team didn't have a lot of confidence," Artest said. "Everybody is on the same page, (and) now our record is showing it. I feel like I was only a part of everything. We're going through everything together and really making a push." Sacramento took a 76-65 lead with a 13-2 run in the third quarter on baskets from six different players. Memphis rallied back with nine points from longtime Kings guard Bobby Jackson in just 3½ minutes of the fourth quarter. But when Jackson left the game with a bruised rib muscle, Artest took over, finishing his 10-point burst with a fast-break score on a sublime bounce pass from Bibby. The Kings' 300th straight sellout crowd cheered wildly for Artest and a reshuffled team that's getting it together quicker than even its coach imagined. "When you look at the team since we made the trade, we were in games, but we just couldn't get over the hump," Kings coach Rick Adelman said. "The team's really getting accustomed to what we've got to do to win. We think we can beat anybody at this point. ... There's expectations for us now, and that's a good thing. When there's no expectations, it's no fun. It's drudgery." The Kings (31-31) got back to .500 for the first time since Nov. 29, when they were 7-7, with their 12th victory in 16 games. Shareef Abdur-Rahim and Kevin Martin scored 13 points apiece for the Kings, who used just seven players. Pau Gasol had 26 points, 12 rebounds and eight assists for the Grizzlies, who finished a four-game West Coast road trip with their second loss in six games. The franchise has won at Arco Arena just once -- when the Vancouver Grizzlies did it in overtime on April 19, 1998. "They have always had one of the most talented teams in the league, and they're starting to put it all together now," Memphis' Shane Battier said. "You can't turn the ball over 19 times in Arco Arena and give up 20 offensive rebounds and expect to win. We shot the ball well, but made all of the other mental mistakes." After winning four of five games on a galvanizing road trip, the Kings returned for a three-game homestand with more of the tough-nosed defense and balanced scoring that's put them back in the postseason chase. The win and New Orleans' loss to Indiana put Sacramento just a half-game behind the Hornets for the Western Conference's final playoff spot. Memphis is in sixth place in the playoff race, with a six-game homestand starting Sunday against Philadelphia. "You can only hang in a close game for so long before those things catch up to you," coach Mike Fratello said. "This was frustrating, but hopefully it's a learning experience." Eddie Jones missed his third straight game for Memphis with a left foot injury. Bonzi Wells left the game for Sacramento in the fourth quarter with cramps in his calves.

Game notes
The Kings have the longest active sellout streak in the NBA. ... Sacramento's Bibby, Wells and Abdur-Rahim all are former Grizzlies. Abdur-Rahim still is the leading rebounder in franchise history with 3,070, but Gasol (3,020) should pass him this month. ... Abdur-Rahim made a 3-pointer from midcourt, but it came after the third-quarter buzzer. Abdur-Rahim knew it, but grinningly cajoled referee James Capers to "check that (replay), come on!"
